com.cyc.kb.wrapper

Class KbTermWrapper

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.cyc.kb.wrapper.KbObjectWrapper
      • com.cyc.kb.wrapper.KbTermWrapper
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    KbObject, KbObject.KbObjectWithArity, KbTerm
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    KbCollectionWrapper, KbIndividualWrapper

    public abstract class KbTermWrapper
extends KbObjectWrapper
implements KbTerm
    An abstract base class for implementing KbTerms per the decorator pattern. To use, extend this class and implement the wrapped() method to return the wrapped object.

        public <O> O replaceTerms(Map substitutions)
                   throws KbTypeException,
                          CreateException
        Description copied from interface: KbTerm
        Non-destructively replace a set of objects within a non-atomic term. This does not modify the original term, but instead returns a new one. Any KBObject or Java

        Note: a common use of this method is to replace indexical terms, so you may want to see KbObject.isIndexical() for more details about them. However, this method can be used to replace any element within a term, not just indexicals.

      • getArity

        public Integer getArity()
        Description copied from interface: KbObject.KbObjectWithArity
        Returns the syntactic arity of this object. If it has a getRelation applied to some arguments (i.e. it's a Sentence, an Assertion, or a functional term), the arity is the number of arguments. By convention, Cyc constants have a formula arity of 0.
        Specified by:
        getArity in interface KbObject.KbObjectWithArity
        Returns:
        the arity of this object, null if not a Cyc constant, functional term, Sentence, or Assertion

      • getArgument

        public <O> O getArgument(int argPosition)
                  throws KbTypeException,
                         CreateException,
                         UnsupportedOperationException
        Description copied from interface: KbObject.KbObjectWithArity
        Gets the object in argPosition argument position of this KbObject as an object of type O. This method works for Sentences and Assertions, as well as non-atomic KbTerms. However, because a constant has no "arguments", calling this method on a KbObject representing a Cyc constant will result in a KbException.
        Specified by:
        getArgument in interface KbObject.KbObjectWithArity
        Type Parameters:
        O - the object type
        Parameters:
        argPosition - the argument position of the object returned
        Returns:
        the object at getPos as a O
        Throws:
        KbTypeException
        CreateException
        UnsupportedOperationException - if getArgument is called on Atomic terms. Do not use this to test for term atomicity, use KbObject.isAtomic() instead.

      • addComment

        public Fact addComment(String comment,
                       Context ctx)
                throws KbTypeException,
                       CreateException
        Description copied from interface: KbTerm
        Add a new comment for this in the context specified

        In the CycKB comments can be added only on #$CycLIndexedTerms, which include CycLReifiableDenotationalTerm and CycLAssertion. An exception will be thrown if attempted to add a comment on Quoted terms, Sentence, Variable and Symbol. This means that only subclasses of KbTerm and Assertion can have comments.

        Specified by:
        addComment in interface KbTerm
        Parameters:
        comment - the comment string
        ctx - the context where the comment is created. Cannot be null.
        Returns:
        the fact created
        Throws:
        KbTypeException
        CreateException

      • instantiatesSentence

        public Sentence instantiatesSentence(KbCollection collection)
                              throws KbTypeException,
                                     CreateException
        Description copied from interface: KbTerm
        This method returns the Sentence (#$isa this collection). The key difference between this and KbTerm.instantiates(com.cyc.kb.KbCollection) is that, this method does not make any assertion in the KB. The sentence form of the assertion is generally useful when seeking user feedback before asserting into the KB. Use Sentence.assertIn(com.cyc.kb.Context) to assert the sentence in a Context.
        Specified by:
        instantiatesSentence in interface KbTerm
        Parameters:
        collection - the collection of which this KbIndividual is an instance
        Returns:
        the #$isa sentence between this and col
        Throws:
        KbTypeException
        CreateException
